# Login and Logout üö™

Django provides built-in views, but you usually want to wrap them in your own logic or templates.

```django
from django.contrib.auth import authenticate, login, logout

def login_view(request):
    # ... get username/pass from form ...
    user = authenticate(username=u, password=p)
    if user is not None:
        login(request, user)
        # User is now logged in!
        return redirect('home')
    else:
        # Invalid login

def logout_view(request):
    logout(request)
    return redirect('login')
```

# Limiting Access üõë

How do you stop non-logged-in users from seeing a page?

## Using Decorators
```django
from django.contrib.auth.decorators import login_required

@login_required
def private_dashboard(request):
    return render(request, 'dashboard.html')
```
If a user isn't logged in, they are redirected to `LOGIN_URL` (defined in settings).

## In Templates
```html
{% if user.is_authenticated %}
    <p>Welcome, {{ user.username }}</p>
{% else %}
    <a href="{% url 'login' %}">Login</a>
{% endif %}
```
